	Starting with 1 and spiralling anticlockwise in the following way, a square spiral with side length 7 is formed.
	\begin{center}
		\medskip%
		\begin{center}\ttfamily%
			\begin{tabular}{rrrrrrr}
				\textcolor{cudred}{37} &                    36  &                    35  & 34 &                    33  &                    32  & \textcolor{cudred}{31} \\%
				\relax             38  & \textcolor{cudred}{17} &                    16  & 15 &                    14  & \textcolor{cudred}{13} &                    30  \\%
				\relax             39  &                    18  & \textcolor{cudred}{ 5} &  4 & \textcolor{cudred}{ 3} &                    12  &                    29  \\%
				\relax             40  &                    19  &                     6  &  1 &                     2  &                    11  &                    28  \\%
				\relax             41  &                    20  & \textcolor{cudred}{ 7} &  8 &                     9  &                    10  &                    27  \\%
				\relax             42  &                    21  &                    22  & 23 &                    24  &                    25  &                    26  \\%
				\textcolor{cudred}{43} &                    44  &                    45  & 46 &                    47  &                    48  &                    49
			\end{tabular}
		\end{center}
		\medskip%
	\end{center}
	It is interesting to note that the odd squares lie along the bottom right diagonal, but what is more interesting is that 8 out of the 13 numbers lying along both diagonals are prime; that is, a ratio of \( 8 \fracslash 13 \approx 62\mathpercent \)%.

	If one complete new layer is wrapped around the spiral above, a square spiral with side length 9 will be formed.
	If this process is continued, what is the side length of the square spiral for which the ratio of primes along both diagonals first falls below \( 10\mathpercent \)?
